        <h3>Inactivated or Dead Vaccines</h3>
        <p>These vaccines do not contain live bacteria or viruses, only dead bacteria, inactivated viruses or fragments of bacteria or viruses which are not functional on their own. As they are not active, the body will not have as strong an immune response to them, so adjuvants are added to the vaccine to trigger a response to the vaccine components. Inactivated vaccines also tend to need boosters to increase the level of protection to the required level, as each vaccination gives partial protection that increases with the next.</p>
    </div>
    <br />
    <div class="maindiv">
        <h3>mRNA Vaccines</h3>
        <p>A new type of vaccine, mRNA vaccines simulate a temporary viral infection without containing any actual viruses or modifying DNA. Cells use DNA for normal function, growth, and division, passing on DNA to the next generation, but they use mRNA to transport messages from DNA to ribosomes, the protein synthesis parts of the cell. mRNA molecules are temporary and do not last long after they are used. mRNA vaccines insert these messenger molecules into some cells, causing them to produce viral proteins which are then detected by the immune system, which learns to recognise the proteins on the actual virus the next time viruses are encountered.</p>
